<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="87" type="type protologue">
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="87">Type protologue.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="87">
Im Hochgebirge, auf sumpfigen Wiesen, auf Urgestein, 5500 ft, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="87">C. Koch</emphasis>
s.n. (holotype: B, probably destroyed).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="88" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="88">
<pageBreakToken pageId="19" pageNumber="88" start="start">Note</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="88">
There is no location in the species protologue beyond the article title &quot;Beitrage zu einer Flora des Orients&quot;. 
<bibRefCitation author="Tzvelev, NN" journalOrPublisher="Botaniceski Zurnal (Moscow &amp; Leningrad)" pageId="23" pageNumber="92" refId="B67" refString="Tzvelev, NN, 1976. Zlaki SSSR. Nauka Publishers, Leningrad Section, Leningrad, 1-788 [English translation: 1983. Grasses of the Soviet Union, 2 vols. Amerind Publishing Co. New Delhi.]" title="Zlaki SSSR. Nauka Publishers, Leningrad Section, Leningrad, 1 - 788 [English translation: 1983. Grasses of the Soviet Union, 2 vols. Amerind Publishing Co. New Delhi.]" year="1976">Tzvelev (1976)</bibRefCitation>
indicated this name and the next, 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Festuca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Festuca polygama" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="polygama">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="88">Festuca polygama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, probably apply to 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Eremopoa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eremopoa persica" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="88" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="88">Eremopoa persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and that the types of these were in Berlin (B). Clayton et al. 2002+ (GrassBase) reflect the same information. RJS was unable to locate type material of either of these two names at B, P or via internet searches.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
